Disable FD bookkeeping in the polling crate's kqueue backend.

polling 3.11 added a HashSet to reject duplicate FD registrations, to
match epoll's EEXIST behaviour. The problem is that kqueue removes FD
registrations automatically when an FD is closed, but the HashSet is
only cleaned up on an explicit delete call. When the kernel reuses a
freed FD number for a new socket, `add()` rejects it with AlreadyExists
even though kqueue itself would accept it.

This shows up in niri as "error making IPC stream async" warnings and
as a crash at src/utils/transaction.rs:119 (an insert_source().unwrap()
that hits the spurious error). It is triggered easily by bars that
open short-lived IPC connections to niri, such as waybar or eww.

Upstream issue: https://github.com/smol-rs/polling/issues/262

Make the bookkeeping methods no-ops. kqueue's own duplicate rejection
is sufficient.

--- a/src/kqueue.rs
+++ b/src/kqueue.rs
@@ -18,10 +18,10 @@
     /// File descriptor for the kqueue instance.
     kqueue_fd: OwnedFd,

-    /// List of sources currently registered in this poller.
-    ///
-    /// This is used to make sure the same source is not registered twice.
-    sources: RwLock<HashSet<SourceId>>,
+    /// FD tracking disabled on kqueue. The original HashMap leaked stale
+    /// entries when FDs were closed by the OS, so reusing those FD numbers
+    /// later produced spurious AlreadyExists errors. See smol-rs/polling#262.
+    _sources: RwLock<HashSet<SourceId>>,

     /// Notification pipe for waking up the poller.
     ///
@@ -56,7 +56,7 @@

         let poller = Poller {
             kqueue_fd,
-            sources: RwLock::new(HashSet::new()),
+            _sources: RwLock::new(HashSet::new()),
             notify: notify::Notify::new()?,
         };

